               <desc type="building-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000063-1">
                     The base of the Jin dynasty Celestial Kings Hall  is made of stone with a height of 1.5 meters. The hall is three bays wide and four rafters deep with a single-eave <term ref="/keyword/k000146">overhanging-gable roof (xuanshan 懸山頂)</term>.  Inside of the hall, there are four <term ref="/keyword/k000107">rafters (chuanfu 椽栿)</term> and the space are equally divided into two parts by three columns (fenxincao 分心槽). The tops of the <term ref="/keyword/k000111">eaves pillars (yanzhu 簷柱)</term> are rounded with a sharp narrowing or entasis (juansha 卷殺). The front eaves pillars support  5-<term ref="/keyword/k000013">puzuo (鋪作)</term> <term ref="/keyword/k000019">bracket sets (dougong 斗拱)</term> with double <term ref="/keyword/k000178">slanted arma  (xia’ang 下昂)</term>. On the other hand, the back eaves pillars only support single <term ref="/keyword/k000103">slaned arms (ang 昂)</term> and single perpendicular bracket arm (chaogong 抄栱). There is only one <term ref="/keyword/k000105">intercolumnar bracketing (bujian puzuo 補間鋪作)</term> in the  <term ref="/keyword/k000153">central bay (dangxinjian 當心間)</term>. The Door and windows are built under the front eaves. The central bay has a single-panel door (banmen 板門) and the two secondary bays have mullioned windows (zhilingchuang 直欞窗). 
                  </p>
               </desc>  
